{
  "answer": "**No works in the corpus contain explicit reflection—i.e., philosophical discussion or analysis—on the relation between learning (or knowledge, wisdom, education, or Vedic study) and authority (or rule, power, judgment, or governance).**\n\nThe search yielded scattered mentions where learning serves as a *qualification* for roles involving authority (e.g., judges, advisors, priests, or kings must possess Vedic learning or wisdom), primarily in the ancient Indic *Smṛti* law codes.[^1][^2][^3][^4] These are prescriptive rules, not reflective ponderings on why or how learning justifies, enables, limits, or derives from authority (as in, e.g., Plato's philosopher-kings). Poetic or economic works occasionally juxtapose the terms but without explicit linkage or reflection.[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, ch. 1 (e.g., excluding those \"destitute of learning\" from legal consultation; Brahmin \"of great learning\" as decider). [/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-3181f4]\n[^2]: *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch. 1 (e.g., authority of Vedic experts in rites and assemblies). [/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-e0ca24]\n[^3]: *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, ch. 2 (kings' minds affected by \"abundance of valor, learning, and wealth... and power\"). [/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/02/translation/#p-8c3061]\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, chs. 1–2 (Brahmins assigned \"teaching and studying\"; study as *tapas* conferring status). [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-71a5c2]\n[^5]: E.g., *Elene*, ch. 1 (Hebrews \"chosen... for learning\"); *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 22 (\"Education and Its Consequences,\" satirical on modern learning). [/works/cynewulf-elene-d2d132/01/translation/#p-7b1c1f]",
